<TEXT>
a portrait of a beardless abraham lincoln the 
first portrait ever painted of him has been discovered by a 
collector of lincoln memorabilia american heritage magazine 
reported 
the portrait appears in the magazines march issue 
it was painted from life in 1856 by dr philip o jenkins a 
physician and amateur artist before lincoln was nationally known 
collectors james l swanson and lloyd ostendorf said 
lincoln became president in 1861 
swanson tracked down the portrait in the illinois home of an 
86yearold distant relative of the artist 
there at the end of the parlor was abraham lincoln 
sixteenth president of the united states he writes 
but this was not bearded father abraham the great emancipator 
and civil war president swanson said it was the image of 
another man abe lincoln of illinois prominent lawyer and 
ambitious politician 
the canvas captured lincoln as he would have looked in his 
office in court or at a political event on any day in the 1850s 
cleanshaven wearing a dark frock coat white shirt and tie 
the article describes the processes swanson went through to 
verify his finding 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

