<TEXT>
the american society of newspaper editors has 
announced five winners of its 1989 distinguished writing awards 
the journalists selected from among 500 applicants will 
receive cash awards of 2500 each during the asnes annual 
convention april 36 
the winners announced sunday are 
terrie claflin staff writer for the medford ore mail 
tribune for nondeadline writing claflin wrote four stories that 
chronicled the short life of a braindamaged foster child whose 
biological mother is a drug addict 
diana griego erwin columnist for the orange county register 
santa ana calif for commentary and column writing her columns 
included one about a hispanic laborer who had difficulty getting a 
drivers license because of his poor english 
samuel francis the washington times for editorial writing 
some of the editorials written by francis who won the award for 
the second straight year focused on conservative themes such as 
support for legislation establishing a review process for the 
national endowment for the arts 
linnet myers reporter for the chicago tribune state and 
local government reporting myers wrote a threepart series 
reviewing the parade of people through chicagos criminal court 
system 
david von drehle reporter for the miami herald deadline 
writing von drehle was cited for his firstperson account of 
hurricane hugos assault on charleston sc 
</TEXT>
