<DOCNO> AP900226-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
inside the former local communist party 
headquarters 17 opposition groups work under the same roof but 
with different visions of how to rebuild east germany after the 
nations first free elections next month 
environmentalists feminists the wellknown new forum and even 
a lone conservative group all rent office space from the communists 
in the neogothic building renamed democracy house after the 
communists moved out in january 
its a little chaotic here campaign worker jana reuter of 
new forum said friday its taking a while to get the hang of 
things 
others praise the camaraderie and conveniences of similar groups 
working under one roof 
for groups that work together being in one building has big 
advantages said thomas voit of the leftistoriented party 
democracy now its easy to meet quickly and exchange ideas or 
discuss campaign details 
with less than three weeks to go before the march 18 elections 
democracy houses winding halls are buzzing with commotion 
on the third floor friday night the conservative party 
democratic awakening was having an organizational meeting one 
floor higher leaders of the east german greens gathered 
it sometimes seems theres a party or group for everyone 
the social democrats want to follow in the footsteps of their 
western counterparts led by willy brandt they are leading in the 
polls 
there are christian democrats free democrats and the 
communists although the latter have changed their name to the 
pleasantsounding party of democratic socialism as they seek to 
break from their stalinist past 
but there are others as well including the united leftists the 
independent womens association and the initiative for peace and 
human rights 
under present laws in east germany a political organization 
does not have to be a party to run for or hold office 
some have warned that the splintering could lead to an inability 
to govern 
west german interior minister wolfgang schaeuble has cautioned 
the united states that difficulties are expected in forming an east 
german government 
it is conceivable that there will be no more east german 
government after march 18 the bonn daily newspaper die welt on 
friday quoted schaeuble as saying 
some groups in democracy house say they are aware of the 
confusion but dont know how else to manage given the brief time 
until the elections and the pressing problems east germany must 
begin solving 
throughout east germany groups and organizations have been 
running campaigns from makeshift offices many of them lacking 
essentials like typewriters to say nothing of photocopying 
machines 
were not pleased to have to work under so much pressure with 
so little time said pastor rainer eppelmann himself one of the 
founding members of the prodemocracy movement and a minister in 
the current caretaker government 
his democratic awakening party has helped lessen the splintering 
somewhat by forming an election alliance with two other 
conservative parties the alliance is supported by west german 
chancellor helmut kohls christian democratic union 
the alliance favors establishing a marketoriented economy 
monetary union and unification with west germany as soon as 
possible socialism never again is one of its slogans 
three leftistoriented groups in democracy house also have 
formed an alliance new forum and the initiative for peace and 
human rights have teamed up with democracy now to form buendnis 90 
alliance 90 
a marketoriented economy yes but not as a dismantling of 
social security unification yes but not as annexation 
alliance 90 says in a campaign paper 
the heady rush toward democracy in east germany has forced the 
emerging political groups to learn about democracy on the run 
from the point of view of party organization it would have 
been better to hold the elections later eppelmann said with a 
sigh but considering the dynamic rate of developments here the 
march 18 date is a good thing 
</TEXT>
