<DOCNO> AP900226-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the romanian revolution has been the 
bloodiest and most chaotic of the upheavals in the soviet bloc 
some of the turmoil seems to stem from the nations history of 
brutal authoritarianism but government critics say mistakes by 
romanias new leaders have also played a role 
two months after its anticommunist uprising romanias fragile 
governing coalition is struggling to keep the peace several 
violent demonstrations saw hundreds of people storm government 
headquarters 
on wednesday a national peasants party official said two party 
activists had been killed in recent weeks apparently for political 
reasons in may elections that traditionally anticommunist party 
will likely prove the strongest challenger to the national 
salvation front 
the front took power after the overthrow and execution of 
president nicolae ceausescu and has since added other parties to 
its provisional government 
none of the other five rapidly democratizing countries in the 
east bloc have seen the violence romania has hundreds perhaps 
thousands are thought to have died in revolutionary battles 
pitting revolutionaries against ceausescu 
no other country however had a ceausescu under a 
quartercentury of his rule romanias 23 million people slid deep 
into economic misery and suffered political repression unmatched 
elsewhere in the bloc 
before ceausescu romania was under the control of one dictator 
or another for most of its 2000year history save for 60 years of 
political pluralism at the turn of the century 
the effect of the long period of despotism was to rob romanians 
of even the slim experience with democracy that many other eastern 
european countries had 
after world war ii under ceausescu the communist dictators 
repression of government opponents wiped out any major opposition 
leaders who could fill the power vacuum after his downfall dec 22 
other eastern european nations had at least some strong dissidents 
who survived their communist regimes 
ceausescus disastrous political legacy is still haunting 
us octavian paler a leading writer and editor of the newspaper 
romania libera said in a recent editorial we must pay a high 
price for the lack of a noncommunist opposition suspicion fear 
and little democratic tradition historically 
after the revolution rivalries broke out between supporters of 
the national salvation front and its opponents 
a loose grouping of excommunists technocrats and former 
dissidents the front ran the country alone for a few weeks but 
its initial reluctance to share power enraged major opposition 
parties and wide sectors of the population who feared the 
relatively high proportion of communists in its ranks made it a 
possible vehicle for a new totalitarian takeover the front was 
eventually forced to share power with nearly 40 new political 
parties 
suspicion of front motives increased after interim president and 
front leader ion iliescu said the group which most people viewed 
as only an interim government would take part in the may 20 
elections initially it had said it had no plans to do so 
following a violent profront demonstration jan 29 several 
opposition parties accused the front of communist tactics such as 
busing in truckloads of supporters blaming the other parties for 
violence and buying support with money and whiskey 
the front moved to redress many grievances during its sixweek 
tenure as the countrys sole government 
it replaced ceausescus most hated laws opened the borders for 
romanians to travel allowed protest demonstrations lifted 
censorship and released political and ordinary prisoners 
but even those moves drew criticism 
they let free the thieves and ordinary criminals and now its 
dangerous to move around freely after sunset said marin stelian 
a bucharest typographer 
adding to the distrust is fear that vestiges of the horrible 
past continue to exist 
a group of 46 intellectuals expressed worry in early february 
that securitate secret policemen who terrorized the country under 
ceausescu still wield secret power 
in an open letter to the new council of national unity which is 
to act as a parliament until the elections the intellectuals said 
nobody can talk about the victory of the revolution when fear 
physical and psychological threats go on 
the depth of concern about the future was evident in remarks 
made by iliescu in the wake of the feb 18 demonstration in which 
some soldiers attempting to keep the mob away from government 
headquarters were injured 
if the army and police dont have the legal ability to 
maintain order people will feel it necessary to defend themselves 
we could become like lebanon and anarchy could lead us to total 
chaos he said in a public address 
romanias only previous brush with democracy occurred in a 
60year span that began in the 1880s political parties were 
allowed to operate under a constitutional monarchy but even then 
the king remained the main figure in decisionmaking until the nazi 
takeover in 1940 and full totalitarianism 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
viorel urma now based in vienna worked for 14 
years for the associated press in bucharest 
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

