<DOCNO> AP900226-0013 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bt collins says hes living proof that 
malathion poses no health risks to southern californians whose 
neighborhoods are being sprayed with the pesticide to wipe out the 
cropdestroying medfly 
as head of the california conservation corps during a 1981 
medfly infestation collins was so sure malathion was safe that he 
drank a diluted glass of it in front of corps members wary about 
picking malathionsprayed fruit 
i offered to do it again said collins now an 
aliveandwell state chief deputy treasurer i dont think the 
citizens in los angeles have a clue as to how disastrous it could 
be if that fly gets to bakersfield at the foot of the 
agriculturallyrich central valley 
perhaps the state should consider taking him up on his offer 
little else has persuaded southern californians that aerial 
malathion spraying should continue to protect agricultural areas 
from the mediterranean fruit fly 
as one city after another joined the revolt last week against 
the aerial spraying state officials were faced with a severe 
credibility gap and no apparent sign of converting the dubious 
critics and supporters of the spraying say the public relations 
effort has suffered from a late start some bad press a 
mediasavvy opposition and mixed and muddled messages from 
officials 
ill tell you they lost an enormous amount of credibility in 
pasadena said city director rick cole who complained the state 
broke its promise to finish spraying before commuters leave in the 
morning for work 
the department of food and agriculture ordered the spraying of 
400 square miles following the discovery of mediterranean fruit 
flies last august 
officials say the eradication program is needed to protect 
californias 165 billion agricultural business they also say the 
sticky mixture of malathion and corn syrup bait poses no health 
risk in small heavily diluted doses a third of an ounce of the 
mixture is dropped over an entire city block 
its safe its safe its safe weve been saying it over and 
over again said gera curry a food and agriculture department 
spokeswoman 
but southern californians arent buying the message 
a recent los angeles times poll found that 57 percent of los 
angeles and orange county residents want the spraying stopped and 
only one in seven strongly support it 
part of the problem critics said is that the state failed to 
spend enough time explaining its position on health risks and did 
not listen to concerns before the spraying began 
state officials said they had to move quickly because any delay 
in spraying even under court order could prove fatal for 
farming 
the medfly wont wait for a temporary restraining order 
said dr peter kurtz a senior medical coordinator with the food 
and agriculture department 
while the state hurried to spray opponents built momentum 
they were aided by media reports damaging the states position 
including charges by the coauthor of a state study who said it was 
edited to understate the health risks the report was often cited 
to support claims that malathion is safe 
in recent weeks a grassroots effort led mainly by concerned 
homeowners has grabbed attention by recruiting famous faces such 
as most of the cast of televisions cheers 
politicians responded by holding public hearings on malathion 
spraying and scientists countered the official line that malathion 
is absolutely safe 
i think that aerial spraying in densely populated areas is 
absolutely ridiculous said dr donald dahlsten a university of 
californiaberkeley entomologist in testimony before the los 
angeles city council 
the state also has used scientists as spokespeople but that has 
posed its own problems scientists are reluctant to speak outside 
of their area of expertise or to give the kind of absolute 
assurances nervous people want 
if youre a scientist you dont use the word safe said 
ms curry the agriculture department spokeswoman the word 
safe is not in a scientists vocabulary 
</TEXT>
