<TEXT>
frigid weather chilled december shipments a 
little but 1989 still was the secondhottest farm export year on 
record thus adding further stature to trade policy debate on 
capitol hill 
overall the agriculture department tallied farm export values 
at just under 40 billion up 77 percent from 1988 that was the 
best dollar performance since 1981 when export values were a record 
433 billion 
exports in december remained strong but did drop 94 million 
from the november level 
unusually cold weather contributed to the decline the usda 
reported decreases in corn soybeans meat rice fruits nuts 
and tobacco more than offset increases in wheat animal feeds 
soybean meal cotton vegetable oils barley and cattle hides 
although the tabulation was for the calendar year the 
department bases its annual forecasts and most analysis on figures 
for the fiscal year which runs from oct 1 through the next sept 
30 
in the last fiscal year for example farm export values totaled 
about 397 billion also the most since 1981 the forecast for the 
198990 fiscal year is for exports to decline to around 38 billion 
the report last week by the departments economic research 
service did not include a forecast for calendar 1990 
but in reviewing what happened in 1989 the agency noted that 
last years commodity export value represented the third 
consecutive yeartoyear increase since exports bottomed out at 
262 billion in 1986 the low point for the 1980s 
exports have been recognized for many years as vital to american 
farmers and are a central issue in the bush administrations 
strategy for 1990 farm legislation 
ongoing multilateral uruguay round negotiations under the 
general agreement on tariffs and trade are aimed at reducing 
barriers that impede exports and imports 
meanwhile several usda programs notably the export enhancement 
program or eep have been used to boost us shipments into 
selected countries where foreign competitors mainly the european 
economic community have been selling products at subsidized 
prices 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter told the house agriculture 
committee last week that the 1990 farm bill should extend export 
programs that have helped boost us exports since the current farm 
law was approved in 1985 
but yeutter added that after completion of the uruguay round 
all programs will be reassessed 
yeutter said the administration wants to continue eep which 
offers designated us commodities to selected target countries at 
subsidized prices but he said the program should be reauthorized 
without mandated levels or programming requirements 
we want our competitors especially in the european community 
to know that we stand ready to use this program to the maximum 
extent he said we want them to phase out their export subsidy 
practices which have severely distorted world markets for many 
years 
