<TEXT>
americans are smoking fewer cigarettes but an 
agriculture department economist says demand continues to grow in 
the rest of the world 
last year the per capita use of cigarettes in the united states 
was estimated at 2936 pieces or fewer than 149 packs of 20 
cigarettes each down about 5 percent from the 1988 rate 
the per capita use has declined for 16 straight years said 
verner grise of the departments economic research service at its 
peak in 1963 use averaged 4345 cigarettes or more than 217 packs 
per capita consumption is based on all persons 18 or older 
smokers and nonsmokers alike it does not indicate actual smoking 
habits and is used by the agency for yeartoyear comparisons 
but world cigarette trade increased about 12 percent grise said 
in the march issue of farmline magazine 
shipments from the united states west germany the 
netherlands hong kong which is also an importer and the united 
kingdom were up while those from bulgaria and belgiumluxembourg 
were down he said together these seven countries account for 
about 84 percent of total world exports 
among the cigarette importing countries the most important 
markets are the soviet union france japan italy hong kong and 
turkey 
during the first nine months of 1989 us cigarette exports 
were up 16 percent from a year earlier with all the major markets 
buying more grise said in the relatively small markets sales 
also rose in south america but declined in australiaoceania and 
canada 
