<TEXT>
getting agreement in washington on the need 
for a civil rights bill is proving almost ridiculously easy but 
its a little tougher to find an accord on what the measure should 
say 
i dont believe we have to overhaul the american legal system 
to ensure equality says sen orrin hatch rutah 
he and other conservatives say the sweeping proposal backed by 
the civil rights community to remedy workplace bias against 
minorities and women goes too far and needs to be limited in scope 
and yet civil rights supporters say the supreme court itself 
overhauled much of the us civil rights law last year in a series 
of rulings on job bias cases 
civil rights forces say those decisions from a supreme court 
whose conservatism deepened considerably in the reagan era 
represent the most severe setback in years for civil rights in the 
workplace they say the bill they support would merely restore the 
previous legal standards 
the supreme court rulings came at a time when opinion polls show 
an easing of worry about civil rights among white americans and 
that may in part explain the bills popularity on capitol hill 
it has gained broad sponsorship in both the house and senate 
including more than a smattering of republicans 
critics contend the measure is guaranteed to usher in racial 
hiring quotas an idea that would be much harder to sell in 
congress but sponsors declare that nothing in the bills language 
requires hiring quotas 
almost everyone agrees change is needed i have no doubt that 
more needs to be done to combat the evil of discrimination in our 
society says hatch as a senior member of the senate labor and 
judiciary committees he could play a pivotal role in any eventual 
negotiations on the issue 
the bush administration already is recommending a bill that 
would overturn two of last years decisions but that does not 
satisfy sen edward m kennedy dmass and other bill sponsors 
the administration cannot stop there or its response will be 
inadequate says kennedy 
the administration and the bill sponsors agree that something 
must be done about the supreme courts decision in the socalled 
patterson case 
the case concerns brenda patterson a former credit union filing 
clerk from winstonsalem nc she said her bosses harassed her and 
discriminated against her for a decade because she was black 
i was actually told to dust and sweep the office even though 
we had a janitor every day and no white employees were ever told to 
do this she said 
the court ruled that the alleged harassment and discrimination 
was not against the law and that a civil warera statute under 
which she had brought suit did not apply in the case the reaction 
against the decision has been so overwhelming that it appears all 
but certain the law will be changed 
but other cases are more complex 
the lorance case involves discrimination in company seniority 
plans the martin vs wilks decision focuses on courtapproved 
fairhiring agreements 
civil rights forces and conservatives may be most at odds over 
whether changes are needed as a result of the wards cove case 
which involved alleged hiring bias at an alaska salmon cannery 
before the supreme courts decision employers defending 
themselves in hiring discrimination cases had to be able to prove 
they based their actions on business necessity 
now however those who file such lawsuits must prove that the 
employer did not act out of business necessity 
by shifting the burden the supreme court has made it far more 
difficult and expensive for victims of discrimination to challenge 
the barriers they face declares kennedy 
harvard law professor charles fried however says kennedys 
proposed remedy is itself flawed 
first an individual filing such a suit would not be required to 
pinpoint which of the employers hiring practices was the source of 
the discrimination fried says that would encourage lawyers 
representing alleged bias victims to unfurl a long list of 
practices and thus force the employer to defend all of them 
also he adds the bill would require the employer to prove that 
each practice was essential for staying in business that could 
prove too difficult says fried im afraid theyre going to say 
gee we dont want to fuss with this well just hire by quota 
he said 
