<TEXT>
reducing us defense spending will have no 
more impact on the economy than cutting money for education health 
and other programs says a report issued today 
using previously published data economist david gold concludes 
that on average over the past four decades defense spending has 
been a relatively neutral feature of the american economic 
landscape 
golds findings differ from the accepted belief that reducing 
the defense budget which in the latest bush administration 
proposal totals 292 billion for fiscal 1991 will generate revenue 
for other programs and trigger economic growth 
cutting the defense budget will have no more of an impact on 
us investment research and development innovation 
productivity international competitiveness and economic growth 
than will cutting other forms of spending both public and 
private gold said in the report 
the economist who works for the united nations centre on 
transnational corp conducted the study while serving as 
consultant for the defense budget project the nonprofit think 
tank released golds report 
the report challenges the conventional wisdom on both sides 
regarding the impact of defense spending said gordon adams 
director of the defense budget project 
the report said cuts in defense spending may provide funds for 
other programs and if properly handled the economy could benefit 
however ld questioned the argument that the defense budget should 
be cut to promote economic growth 
the defense budget may lie elsewhere in such problems as 
wastsmanagement and in the debate over the actual requirements for 
military forces in a rapidly changing world gold said 
gold also disputed the claim that defense requirements for 
research and development talent have weakened productivity in the 
private sector according to the report the number of scientists 
and engineers who have left civilian work for the military sector 
has declined in recent years despite the defense buildup of the 
1980s 
