<TEXT>
more people convicted of felonies by state 
court juries wind up in prison and stay there longer than those 
found guilty by judges according to a new report 
the justice department analysis issued sunday also found that 89 
percent of convicted felons plead guilty and that they spend less 
time in prison than those who go to trial and are convicted by a 
judge or jury 
the penalties of life in prison or death are meted out to 47 
percent of those convicted by juries of murder or nonnegligent 
manslaughter meanwhile only 15 percent of those who pleaded 
guilty to such charges and 12 percent of those found guilty by a 
judge received those penalties said the report by the departments 
bureau of justice statistics 
it is unclear why defendants convicted by juries were more 
severely punished the study said but it noted that a higher 
percentage of the convictions by juries were for violent offenses 
it said defendants in serious cases violent and nonviolent may 
have been less willing to plead guilty because they expected severe 
penalties in addition prosecutors may have recommended and 
judges may have imposed shorter sentences for those who pled 
compared to those found guilty by trial it said 
the study based on information from 100 counties in 37 states 
regarding all convicted felons sentenced in 1986 cautioned that 
the findings should be considered preliminary because of the 
limited sample size the next survey is to cover 300 jurisdictions 
of the estimated 583000 people convicted of a felony in state 
courts in 1986 89 percent pleaded guilty 8 percent were convicted 
by a jury and 3 percent were found guilty by a judge the report 
says 
but many of the guilty pleas were for lesser offenses with 92 
percent of the larceny convictions and 90 percent of the burglary 
convictions based on guilty pleas but only 58 percent of the 
murder convictions and 68 percent of the rape convictions based on 
such pleas 
felons convicted by a jury were sentenced to an average of 159 
months in prison compared with 103 months when felons were 
convicted by a judge and 72 months for those who pleaded guilty 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the number of people on earth will double in 
39 years unless birth control becomes available to everybody by the 
end of the decade according to a new study 
this is a preventable disaster said sharon l camp vice 
president of the private population crisis committee a 
washingtonbased advocacy group that released the report sunday 
we have what it would take the financial resources and the 
know how to solve the problem and to do so in our childrens 
lifetime but we have to act immediately we cannot dither away 
another decade 
there are about 53 billion people in the world a figure that 
the united nations says could rise to 14 billion before stabilizing 
in the next century the committee said todays population could 
double in 39 years and reach 27 billion by the end of the 21st 
century if present birth and death rates continued unchanged 
stopping population growth at about 9 billion to 10 billion 
people would require use of contraceptives by some 75 percent of 
couples the study estimates but to accomplish that the products 
would have to be available to everyone by the end of this century 
so the average family size could fall to about two children per 
couple early in the 21st century 
the report goes on to estimate the cost of such an effort 
105 billion per year by the year 2000 currently 32 billion is 
spent on family planning in developing countries where most 
population growth is taking place 
universal family planning is a bargain compared to the costs 
of delaying world population stabilization camp said 
