<TEXT>
cambodias warring factions gathered 
today for talks on ending their 11yearold conflict the 
vietnameseinstalled government bolstered by battlefield victories 
against noncommunist guerrillas 
the three days of talks were expected to focus on a possible 
role for the united nations in reaching a settlement with little 
else on the negotiating table asian diplomatic sources said the 
meeting would be a success only if the un role were approved at 
least in principle 
a ceremonial opening was planned in the evening after the 
arrival of foreign minister roland dumas of france a cohost with 
foreign minister ali alatas of indonesia 
a 19nation peace conference in paris last summer opened with 
high hopes only to deadlock largely on the question of how power 
would be shared by the hanoibacked government of premier hun sen 
and the threemember guerrilla coalition 
hun sen has said he would allow the united nations to organize 
elections but not administer the country until polling takes place 
his government has opposed un participation in peace efforts in 
the past because the world body recognizes the guerrilla coalition 
as the legitimate government of cambodia 
vietnam invaded cambodia in late 1978 ending nearly four years 
of rule by the khmer rouge which killed hundreds of thousands of 
peopl as it tried to turn the former french colony into a radical 
agrarian commune 
the vietnamese claim to have pulled all their troops out of 
cambodia in september 
the khmer rouge is the strongest member of the guerrilla 
coalition and there are fears of a recurrence of brutal rule if its 
fighters were to topple the hun sen government 
representing the guerrilla coalition at this weeks talks are 
prince norodom ranariddh on behalf of the faction of his father 
former head of state prince norodom sihanouk khmer rouge vice 
president khieu samphan and former premier son sann head of the 
khmer peoples national liberation front 
also on hand are hun sen vietnamese foreign minister nguyen co 
thach and representatives from laos and the association of 
southeast asian nations brunei indonesia malaysia the 
philippines singapore and thailand 
as the participants gathered news reports quoted noncommunist 
guerrilla commanders as saying they suffered major battlefield 
losses at the hands of the phnom penh army they blamed a halt in 
arms supplies from china for their predicament 
china has been the main supplier of arms to the three guerrilla 
factions it was unclear whether the interruption confirmed by 
western diplomats in bangkok was due to logistics or a policy 
decision 
the guerrilla commanders said that because of their inability 
to stop a government counteroffensive in northwestern cambodia 
thousands of civilians under their control were moving closer to 
the thai border 
the soviet union has been the main supplier of weapons to 
vietnam and the cambodian government 
khieu samphan said in a statement sunday that more than 20000 
vietnamese troops had been sent back into cambodia since hanoi 
announced that all of its troops were withdrawn in september the 
vietnamese troops wore the uniforms of hun sens army he said 
khieu samphan repeated a previous demand for a complete 
withdrawal to prepare for a comprehensive solution asked if he 
thought the talks might be successful he said it would depend on 
vietnam 
vietnams government radio today quoted dumas as saying france 
is significantly expanding economic relations with vietnam largely 
isolated for a decade because of its invasion of cambodia 
dumas who was in vietnam over the weekend said in a joint 
communique that france will give 8 million to vietnam up from 
870000 last year 
