<TEXT>
not since george washington led a surprise 
attack on the hessians in 1776 has there been such a stir over 
crossing the delaware river 
pennsylvania and new jersey are bickering over control of two 
toll bridges linking the states 
the dispute pennsylvania officials argue is about independence 
and sovereignty and taxation without representation and other 
principles associated with the revolutionary war 
officials with the burlington county bridge commission in new 
jersey say its all much simpler than that federal law gives them 
jurisdiction over the bridges the commission needs more money to 
repair or replace them and its fairest to get the money from the 
travelers who use them 
so at the start of the year the commission doubled the tolls to 
50 cents on the taconypalmyra and burlingtonbristol bridges 
spanning the delaware river the commission also moved ahead with 
plans to replace the 59yearold burlingtonbristol span 
the moves drew the ire of lawmakers across the river 
us sen john heinz rpa said the dispute may not dissolve 
our union but he warned the commission had better consult 
pennsylvania citizens if it plans on replacing the 
burlingtonbristol bridge 
we are a nation of many sovereign states heinz said in a 
recent speech on the senate floor although we like to think of 
ourselves as a perfect union there are times when the sovereignty 
leads to fragmentation divisiveness and threats upon the very 
notion of federalism 
the senator also said that raising the tolls amounted to 
taxation without representation 
heinz this month introduced a bill in the senate that would 
require cooperation between both states on any bridge project over 
the delaware river the senate has taken no action on it 
j garfield demarco chairman of the bridge commission did not 
return a reporters telephone calls but stephanie miller a public 
relations consultant for the bridge commission said pennsylvanians 
have been consulted about the bridges and should have nothing to 
complain about anyway 
even at 50 cents miller said the bridges were a bargain 
compared with the two other major delaware river spans where tolls 
are 90 cents 
miller said the commission is using the extra money for 
desperately needed bridge maintenance 
