the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether a federal law requiring some lawsuit losers to pay the 
winners lawyer fees also covers expertwitness fees 
the court will review a ruling that deprived west virginia 
universitys hospital of reimbursement for the 104000 it spent on 
three expert witnesses in successfully suing pennsylvania 
the wvu hospital in morgantown just six miles from the 
pennsylvania state line serves numerous medicaid recipients who 
live in pennsylvania 
the hospital sued pennsylvania officials in 1986 in a dispute 
over the states system of reimbursements for medicaid services 
under the social security act 
us district judge sylvia rambo in 1988 ruled that the 
pennsylvania reimbursement system violated federal law and ordered 
the state to develop a new system 
she also ordered the state to pay 500000 in lawyer fees 
incurred by the hospital including 104000 for expert witnesses 
who testified about deficiencies in the payment system for 
outofstate hospitals 
the philadelphiabased 3rd us court of appeals last sept 5 
set aside that portion of the award representing most of the 
reimbursement for expertwitness fees 
the appeals court said congress in passing the law providing 
lawyerfee awards did not intend to allow reimbursements for 
expertwitness fees 
other federal appeals courts have ruled that congress did intend 
to include reimbursement for such fees 
the 3rd circuit court noted that federal court rules provide for 
the losing side in some cases to pay up to 30 a day for expert 
witnesses employed by the winning side 
the appeals court said the wvu hospital could not be awarded 
more than that daily 30 
in the hospitals appeal acted on today its lawyers relied 
heavily on a supreme court decision last year that said lawyerfee 
awards could take the work of paralegals into account 
just as paralegals assist in the preparation of an attorneys 
work product experts educate counsel and preclude the need for the 
attorney to educate himself which would obviously require more 
time and run up an attorneys fees even more the appeal said 
the case is west virginia university hospitals inc vs casey 
89994 
