poor weather forced the launch of 
shuttle atlantis secret military mission to be scrubbed today for 
the fifth time the most delays since the doomed challenger 
nasa set the next attempt for early wednesday 
peekaboo clouds and erratic winds tantalized nasa with possible 
launch opportunities for almost two hours early today and officials 
kept atlantis and its fiveman crew poised and ready for any 
momentary break in the weather 
but the break never came at 232 am launch director robert 
sieck abandoned the launch attempt and announced nasa would not try 
again until early wednesday 
experts saw little chance that launch weather would improve 
later in the week 
were just in kind of a stalemate because of the weather 
said tom strange an air force weather forecaster he said there 
was only a 20 percent chance of favorable weather on wednesday and 
a 40 percent chance on thursday 
winds and clouds early today were on the very edge of acceptable 
limits and nasa extended a pause in the launch countdown in hopes 
that the weather would improve eventually the winds calmed enough 
for launch but a cloud cover hung on stubbornly and sieck decided 
to give up 
nasa spokesman kyle herring said exhaustion among the 
astronauts launchpad technicians and engineers played a role in 
the decision to delay the next launch attempt until early wednesday 
we just want to give the crews a rest herring said 
atlantis commander navy capt john o creighton said in a 
statement today that the crew was disappointed but we are 
convinced that the launch team and the mission management team made 
the correct decision we are looking forward to the next 
opportunity 
creighton and two of his crew members air force col john h 
casper the pilot and marine lt col david c hilmers planned to 
fly back to the astronaut training base in houston later today to 
practice in a shuttle simulator 
the shuttle mission originally was scheduled to begin last 
thursday two launch attempts were abandoned after creighton 
developed a sore throat and head congestion an attempt early 
saturday was blocked by unacceptable weather conditions 
early sunday with clear skies and ideal weather nasa counted 
down to within 31 seconds of launch and then had to call it off 
when a computer broke down 
this mission has been postponed more times than any shuttle 
flight since challenger which had seven delays and then blew up 
shortly after liftoff on its eighth try on jan 28 1986 all seven 
crew members died 
atlantis flight is a classified military mission as a result 
the precise launch time and length of the flight are secret 
however sources said the spacecraft is to be launched just 
before 1 am est on wednesday is to fly about 4 days and will 
land at edwards air force base in california 
the sources who spoke on condition they not be named said 
atlantis cargo is a 500 million spy satellite capable of taking 
highresolution reconnaissance photos and listening in on 
electronics communications all over the world atlantis is to 
deploy the satellite in an orbit that will carry the craft over 
more of the soviet union than any satellite previously launched by 
a shuttle 
the other crew members are mission specialists air force col 
richard mullane and navy lt cmdr pierre j thuot 
the atlantis flight is to be the 34th shuttle mission the sixth 
classified military flight and the fourth afterdark shuttle 
launch 
