<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear an 
appeal by the mother of a seaman stabbed to death aboard a ship in 
what was described as a vicious attack by another crew member 
the court said it will use the case from new orleans to consider 
increasing the damages ship owners and possibly unions may be 
forced to pay to parents and other heirs of slain sailors 
the issues are whether the heirs are entitled to damages for the 
dead seamans lost future wages and compensation for parents 
loss of society 
the case stems from an incident aboard the archon during its 
maiden voyage while the ship was docked in washington state on july 
18 1984 
the victim ludwick torregano 24 a stewards assistant was 
stabbed or cut at least 62 times by fellow crew member clifford 
melrose 
melrose later was convicted of seconddegree murder in clark 
county wash 
torreganos mother mercedel miles sued the ship owners and 
operators in federal court in new orleans 
ms miles administrator of her sons estate was awarded 
140000 for the pain and suffering torregano endured before his 
death and 7800 for the loss of her sons support 
but the jury refused to order additional damages for the loss of 
torreganos future income or for loss of society by either ms 
miles or the seamans father joseph o torregano 
loss of society is defined as a broad range of mutual benefits 
family members receive from each other including love affection 
care attention companionship comfort and protection 
the 5th us supreme court of appeals last september upheld the 
damages awarded by the jury 
the appeals court also ruled that under maritime law the archon 
was unseaworthy because melrose was among its crew 
the savagery of melroses attack itself leads us to conclude 
that melrose has an especially dangerous disposition the appeals 
court said melrose failed to measure up to the standard of his 
calling and rendered the vessel unseaworthy 
that opened the way for increased damages against the archons 
owners and operators but the appeals court then said that 
torreganos parents are not entitled to compensation for loss of 
his future wages or for their loss of their sons society 
only dependents are entitled to be compensated for loss of 
society when a seaman dies the appeals court said 
the number of plaintiffs who could allege a loss of love and 
affection as a result of the death of a dearly beloved seaman 
aunts and uncles nieces and nephews even friends and lovers 
necessitates that we draw a line between those who may recover for 
loss of society and those who may not the appeals court said 
the appeals court also ruled that the seafarers international 
union may be sued by the ship owners and operators for its role in 
permitting melrose to be hired as a member of the archon crew 
that means the union eventually could be forced to help pay any 
compensation awarded ms miles 
the case is miles vs apex marine 891158 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

