<TEXT>
twentytwo soviet tanks left 
this northern moravian city today beginning the red armys 
withdrawal from czechoslovakia nearly 22 years after moscow sent 
troops to crush prague spring reforms 
few people came to wave goodbye and those who did showed little 
emotion 
a brass band struck up the internationale the communist 
anthem during a brief ceremony inside the soviet base at frenstat 
that kicked off the first complete withdrawal of soviet troops from 
any of moscows allies 
the soviet troops entered czechoslovakia with a warsaw pact 
invasion that smashed the 1968 reforms but in november 1989 a 
peaceful revolution toppled the hardline communists and the new 
government immediately began talks on withdrawing all red army 
troops 
to czechoslovaks the soviet troops meant empty shelves in 
stores polluted water an occasional fight in the pub and a 
reminder that we are not a free country said karel micek a 
spokesman for the civic forum movement 
withdrawal of the 73500 soviet troops stationed on czechoslovak 
territory is to be completed by the end of next year 
the withdrawal from frenstat pod radhostem 110 miles southeast 
of prague was accompanied by a parallel pullout from krnov on the 
czechoslovakpolish border 150 miles east of the czechoslovak 
capital they are to be completed by march 13 and march 25 
respectively 
this is our new peace policy in practice a retreat from 
the policy of confrontation gen vladimir malyshkievich deputy 
chief of the soviet contingent in czechoslovakia said during the 
ceremony 
it is only proper this process starts in the center of europe 
and on the day of the official visit of president vaclav havel in 
the soviet union he said 
havel flew to moscow today for two days of talks with soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev just three days after returning 
from the united states where he met with president bush havel and 
gorbachev are expected to sign the agreement on troop withdrawals 
concluded in prague on feb 22 
the accord provides for a soviet pullout in three stages with a 
decisive part of the contingent leaving the country by the end 
of may the first free elections in czechoslovakia since the 
communists consolidated power in 1948 are due in june 
czechoslovakia originally demanded the withdrawal by the end of 
199o but the soviets citing administrative problems requested 
the deadline be extended until the end of 1991 
the first of the t62 tanks left frenstat by train in the 
afternoon en route to the soviet border 
most probably they will reach the border some time tomorrow 
said stanislav pohoral a defense ministry spokesman 
no official figures have been released on the number of troops 
affected by todays pullbacks but vadim pliska a soviet soldier 
posted in frenstat said some 2000 soldiers and approximately 9o 
tanks were stationed there 
moscow currently has 73500 soldiers 122o tanks 25o5 armored 
vehicles 77 combat aircraft and 146 helicopters stationed on 
czechoslovak soil 
