<TEXT>
teachers want geography a distant subject to 
many young americans to be among the courses required for high 
school graduation according to a survey released monday 
the nationwide survey of 852 elementary and secondary school 
social studies and geography teachers found 86 percent favored 
changing requirements to require that high school students pass a 
geography course in order to graduate eightyseven percent want 
state governments to increase geography requirements 
the rand mcnally report on geography education in america 
conducted by ketchum communications research and measurement comes 
on the heels of the first study of geography education by the 
national assessment of educational progress popularly known as 
the nations report card 
that report said high school seniors have a gap in their 
knowledge of geography with only 37 percent able to find southeast 
asia on a world map the average student could answer just 57 
percent of the questions and the best score among more than 3000 
students tested was 59 percent the report showed 
nine out of 10 teachers polled by rand mcnally said the quality 
of geography education american children currently receive could be 
considered poor or only fair 
unless geography education improves 85 percent of the teachers 
said that us citizens will not be able to adequately understand 
the importance of present and future environmental issues and 83 
percent said that other countries with citizens educated in 
geography will have competitive business advantages over the united 
states 
the survey findings indicate that geography is not receiving 
ample time in the classroom because it is taught as part of a 
broader subject such as history or social studies said dennis 
decock of rand mcnally he said 90 percent of those surveyed said 
more classroom time should be spent on geography 
requiring high school students to pass a geography course to 
graduate is one of the keys to restoring geography teaching to its 
proper role the teachers said 
seventytwo percent of those surveyed said most teachers have 
not received adequate training themselves in geography and 
therefore do not teach it well or at all eightynine percent said 
teachers of geography should be provided supplemental geography 
education 
the teachers surveyed included members of the national council 
for the social studies and the national council for geographic 
education 
rand mcnally a leading producer of maps and geography teaching 
materials said it has established an awards program for teachers 
who display creative classroom approaches to teaching geography 
the program is cosponsored by the national council for geographic 
education and will feature a 10000 cash prize 
</TEXT>
