<TEXT>
a frenchman and a scottishborn american were 
named on monday to share the 1990 wolf prize for physics 
the 100000 award to be presented in the israeli parliament 
may 20 will be given to pierregilles de gennes of the college of 
france in paris and david j thouless of the university of 
washington in seattle the wolf foundation said 
de gennes and thouless were selected for their pioneering 
contributions to our understanding of the organization of complex 
condensedmatter systems the foundation said 
de gennes 57 has held the chair in condensedmatter physics at 
the college of france since 1971 
the foundation praised him for developing basic concepts in the 
physics of macromolecular matter and of liquid crystals 
thouless 55 earned his doctorate in physics at cornell 
university in 1958 he has been in washington state since 1980 
the foundation said he was cited for contributions to 
understanding disordered and twinlayered matter 
winners already have been named in mathematics agriculture 
medicine chemistry and the arts 
the wolf prizes were established in 1975 to honor the late 
ricardo wolf the germanborn inventor immigrated to cuba before 
world war i and later served as its ambassador to israel he died 
in 1981 
