the giant hull of the exxon valdez was 
gashed twice as the tanker lumbered over one set of jagged rocks 
and grounded on another on bligh reef a witness testified today 
george greiner jr formerly of the coast guard showed jurors 
elaborate sets of charts graphs and photographs of the ship in dry 
dock in san diego 
greiner said he tracked the ships course from a number of logs 
kept by the crew and found that its damage was intensified by the 
dramatic shifting of tides in prince william sound as the 987foot 
tanker sat grounded on the reef 
he said the rising tide caused a crushing effect adding to 
the damage 
greiner testified as the trial of joseph hazelwood entered its 
fourth week with prosecutors planning to rest their case against 
the skipper tuesday 
the prosecution claims that hazelwood skipper of the crippled 
ship was reckless in trying to drive it off the reef after the 
march 24 accident 
hazelwoods lawyers contend he never attempted the risky 
maneuver of backing off the reef but was trying to stabilize the 
vessel by moving forward 
prosecutors say that if hazelwood had succeeded in moving it off 
the reef the exxon valdez would have capsized spilling even more 
oil and possibly killing crew members 
the tanker spilled almost 11 million gallons of oil killing 
countless birds fish and other wildlife and blackening hundreds of 
miles of rocky shore 
in addition to greiner prosecutors plan to call experts to 
testify about the effects of alcohol on the body and the figures 
reflected on bloodalcohol tests administered to hazelwood after 
the accident 
hazelwood 43 of huntington ny is charged with second degree 
criminal mischief a felony and three misdemeanors reckless 
endangerment operating a vessel while intoxicated and negligent 
discharge of oil if convicted on all counts he could face a 
maximim of 7 years in prison and 61000 in fines 
hazelwood was not on the bridge when the tanker grounded during 
a tricky passage into scenic prince william sound a third mate who 
was in charge has blamed the accident on the helmsmans failure to 
steer properly 
a key issue in the case is whether hazelwood was drunk when he 
boarded the ship he had spent a day in the port city of valdez and 
was seen by witnesses drinking at a bar called the pipeline club 
but in his first postaccident interview with the coast guard 
played for jurors on friday hazelwood denied drinking anything 
stronger than beer and said he drank nothing at all at the pipeline 
