christian forces skirmished in east 
beirut on monday deadlocking mediation efforts to end the power 
struggle between rival christian leaders and sending hundreds of 
frightened civilians fleeing 
two people died and 10 were wounded in the daylong exchanges of 
sniper fire police said 
that raised the casualty toll to 693 killed and 1925 wounded 
since fighting broke out on jan 30 between the lebanese forces led 
by samir geagea and the army troops of gen michel aoun it is the 
worst fighting between christian factions in the nearly 15yearold 
civil war 
a threeman mediation committee of independent christian leaders 
was unable to stop the shooting and faced major difficulties in 
arranging an overall settlement a police spokesman said on 
condition of anonymity 
the snipers didnt stop shooting although the committee 
members were repeatedly informed by the two headquarters that 
orders had been issued to halt the exchanges the spokesman said 
the committees failure to stabilize a repeatedly violated feb 
17 ceasefire heightened concern that a new round of fighting is 
likely between the factions vying for control of the christian 
enclave north of beirut 
the spokesman said the committee couldnt proceed with its 
plan to reopen roads inside christian east beirut because of the 
clashes 
the committee arranged for some main roads to reopen sunday but 
so far that has been all the mediators have achieved 
the mediation deadlock drove hundreds of christian civilians to 
cross beiruts dividing green line into moslem west beirut and flee 
to eastern and northern lebanon 
the police spokesman said there was a sharp increase in the 
number of evacuees in the afternoon after radio stations reported 
the committee was making no progress in ending the bloodshed 
