<TEXT>
a powersharing agreement forced upon the 
evenly divided republicans and democrats in the indiana house is 
breaking down into bickering and rules fights and may be heading 
for a messy divorce 
it isnt working because apparently there is a basic lack of 
trust said state rep stephen c moberly a republican who for 
years had warned his colleagues about the potential problems in a 
house without a clear majority 
the republicans dont trust the democratic speaker and the 
democrats dont trust the republican speaker because both can 
manipulate the rules to help their party and their agenda said 
moberly 
under the powersharing agreement approved in november 1988 
after an election produced the halfandhalf split the 100seat 
house has republican and democratic speakers who preside on 
alternate days and each house committee has a chairman from each 
party 
that agreement takes a twothirds vote to change and remains in 
effect despite the defection monday of rep frank newkirk from the 
democratic to republican party which gave the gop an edge in 
voting 
legislative leaders boasted at the end of the 1989 session that 
the arrangement worked far better than many had predicted but this 
year the same leaders concede the setup is showing signs of strain 
over the last couple of days its degenerated republican 
house speaker paul s mannweiler said last week i think its 
just sort of unraveled 
democratic speaker michael k phillips isnt as pessimistic but 
concedes the system has its problems 
the arrangements working smoothly we just disagree on the 
process said phillips still nobodys jumped over the front 
desk to try to take over the speakers chair 
both speakers du jour agree there have been problems in 
recent days although neither is willing to share the blame 
mannweiler believes the problems began when the 13 democrats on 
the 26member house ways and means committee refused to attend a 
weeks worth of committee hearings recently because the democrats 
didnt want to consider republicansponsored bills 
that doomed most of the bills except one that republicans 
forced out of committee by using a rarely successful blast motion 
to remove a welfare caseworker bill from the committees 
jurisdiction and send the measure directly to the floor 
mannweiler also faults phillips for failing one day last week to 
hand down 21 committee reports on republican bills that delayed 
consideration of the bills so they couldnt be amended by the full 
house on a day when mannweiler was presiding 
at the same time democrats maintain a list of alleged misdeeds 
by republicans 
last week after democrats blocked a republican bill to cut the 
auto excise tax the gop retaliated with a rare maneuver in which 
they called back for consideration a democratic bill that had 
already been amended on the house floor and removed their 
opponents excise tax proposal from the measure 
phillips protested charging mannweiler with an unprecedented 
and clearly erroneous interpretation of the rules and precedents 
of the house 
democrats also accused republicans of vultureous conduct 
claiming the gop was taking advantage of a temporary 5049 
numerical edge resulting from the death last week of rep g edward 
cook whose successor will be chosen march 4 that margin grew to 
5148 with newkirks defection 
the republicans continue to think they can rewrite the rules 
to satisfy their needs said phillips i also think they would 
not even be attempting this if ed cook were alive and in his seat 
democrats also criticized republicans request last week for an 
attorney generals opinion to determine if 50 votes instead of the 
normal constitutional majority of 51 would be enough to pass a 
bill while the house temporarily has 99 members 
the maneuvering and rare uses of house rules have created an 
uneasy atmosphere house members can regularly be seen flipping 
through the chambers 88page rule book to determine if one side is 
taking advantage of the other 
that is likely to continue during the final six working days of 
the session which must be completed by march 15 
phillips threatened retaliation last week 
you live by the rules you die by the rules he warned 
republicans 
</TEXT>
