<TEXT>
czechoslovak president vaclav havel said he and 
president mikhail s gorbachev established a new basis for 
relations monday and said all soviet troops would be withdrawn from 
czechoslovakia by july 1 1991 
havel the playwright and opposition leader who scripted his 
countrys peaceful return to democracy late last year met with 
gorbachev after arriving on his first official visit to the soviet 
union since he was elected dec 29 as his countrys first 
noncommunist president in 41 years 
the visit coincided with the start of the withdrawal of 73500 
soviet troops still in czechoslovakia 22 years after moscow sent 
its military forces to crush the prague spring reforms 
havel flew to moscow for talks with gorbachev just three days 
after returning from the united states where he met with president 
bush 
at a news conference following the kremlin meeting havel called 
the joint declaration he had signed earlier with gorbachev a very 
important document that would pave the way for a new kind of 
cooperation 
the declaration calls for relations to be developed on the 
basis of equality and complete mutual respect for each others 
state sovereignty tass reported 
gorbachev and havel looked on soviet foreign minister eduard a 
shevardnadze and foreign minister jiri dienstbier of czechoslovakia 
signed the agreement concluded in prague on feb 22 outlining the 
troop withdrawal 
havel said he hoped all of the troops would return to the soviet 
union within one year but that the agreement stipulated they must 
be gone by july 1 1991 
soviet troops spearheaded the 1968 warsaw pact invasion that 
crushed the reforms 
moscow has 73500 soldiers 1220 tanks 2505 armored vehicles 
77 combat aircraft and 146 helicopters stationed on czechoslovak 
soil 
havel said czechoslovakia had offered to help the soviet union 
with the withdrawal by providing free rail and water transport of 
men and equipment and assistance in constructing housing for the 
soldiers in the soviet union where there is a chronic shortage of 
apartments 
economic issues were also raised at plenary talks between 
officials of the two countries and havel said that czechoslovakia 
should not renew cooperation agreements that had been concluded by 
the previous communist government however economic matters were 
not the focus of the trip 
in addition to havel and dienstbier the czechoslovak delegation 
includes defense minister miroslav vacek and interior minister 
richard sacher who is interested in reducing the links between 
officials of his ministry and those of the soviet kgb operative on 
czechoslovak soil 
havel who spent five years in prison for his political 
activities against the totalitarian state an experience that is 
the source and strength of many of his writings appeared to be 
adjusting well to the role of a world statesmen 
he seemed at ease at the news conference and said that during 
his talks with bush and gorbachev that both leaders had recognized 
the special role that czechoslovakia had to play in the center of 
europe 
the czechoslovak model of a peaceful recovery of democracy has 
also won admirers among opposition movements from the soviet 
republic of moldavia to the three baltic republics which are 
pressing for independence from moscow 
during his meeting with gorbachev havel touched on the rapidly 
changing political situation in europe last week in washington he 
had called on the united states to support moves toward democratic 
reform in the soviet union as a contribution to stability in europe 
however he said that he had no specific message from bush for 
gorbachev 
the two leaders also discussed the rapid rapprochement of the 
two germanys 
havel said he told gorbachev the reunification of germany should 
be conducted in a way that would not complicate the whole 
european unification process but would rather service as a motor 
for that process 
on tuesday the former dissident is scheduled to meet with 
yelena bonner widow of andrei sakharov the nobel peace prize 
winner who was a source of inspiration for a generation of 
opposition activists in eastern europe 
</TEXT>
