<TEXT>
the postal service is not violating 
freespeech rights by banning everyone from the red cross to 
political extremists from soliciting donations outside most post 
offices the supreme court was told monday 
justice department lawyer john roberts jr representing the 
postal service said the area outside suburban or rural post 
offices is not a traditional public forum as is the city 
sidewalk outside an urban post office 
most of the nations 35000 post offices have their own 
sidewalks surrounded by parking lots this property is dedicated 
to the postal services use roberts contended its not just 
like a city sidewalk where freespeech rights must be considered 
but washington lawyer jay sekulow disagreed the right to 
solicit classic political speech is not subject to 
architectural design he said a moat cannot be created by this 
intervening parking lot 
at issue in a case from bowie md is a federal regulation 
