other cases 
sekulows clients marsha kokinda and kevin pearl were arrested 
aug 6 1986 after they refused to stop soliciting contributions 
and distributing literature from a table on the sidewalk just 
outside the bowie post office 
the two are volunteers for the national democratic policy 
committee the political arm of an organization headed by political 
extremist lyndon larouche 
they were convicted of violating the federal regulation although 
there was no evidence they had blocked or interfered with people 
entering and leaving the post office about 30 patrons had 
complained about the couples presence 
would there have been any complaints if it were the red 
cross justice anthony m kennedy asked the justice department 
lawyer 
probably not roberts answered although adding that the 
blanket ban on soliciting prevents postal officials from favoring 
some groups over others 
roberts said the regulation is not being enforced against people 
who hand out leaflets seek petition signatures or picket but only 
against those who solicit immediate contributions 
its when you let them ask for money that the crowds come 
out he said 
but roberts said the postal service would not violate 
freespeech rights if it chose to banish from its property all 
activities not linked directly to postal business 
sekulow argued that the postal service never has elected to make 
its property an enclave immune from the first amendment 
when justice sandra day oconnor asked if the postal service 
must allow panhandling on its sidewalks sekulow said beggars have 
the same freespeech rights as anyone else subject to the same 
time place and manner regulations 
oconnor also asked roberts why such time place and manner 
regulations and not a total ban would not be an effective way 
to prevent congestion or inconvenience 
several other justices also voiced concern over the sweep of a 
blanket ban 
why isnt it the regulation overbroad justice byron r 
white asked 
and justice john paul stevens asked is there a history of a 
problem outside the buildings one might argue it the 
regulation is overbroad 
the case is us vs kokinda 882031 
