<TEXT>
the united nations on monday released a largely 
inconclusive report on the human rights situation in iran based on 
the first visit by a special un investigator since it came under 
international scrutiny in 1984 
the 76page report compiled by salvadoran jurist reynaldo 
galindo pohl under a mandate from the un human rights commission 
cites evidence of torture and other gross violations along with 
denials 
but he concedes that in many cases it was not possible to 
conduct an indepth examination during the weeklong stay last 
month and suggests a renewal of his mandate and another visit 
the report lists the names of about 700 people allegedly 
executed in iran most of them in the past two years along with 39 
people alleged to have been executed by the iraqbased mujahedeen 
resistance iranian media reports have said that more than 1300 
were executed in iran in slightly less than one year and western 
human rights groups have carried much higher estimates 
galindo pohl said that barring specific proof he rules out 
allegations that political prisoners had been executed under false 
charges of drug trafficking 
he said there had been no public executions for five months 
although probably hundreds are still awaiting execution he 
added that he requested clemency for them and that he gained the 
impression that this harsh policy of executions could become a 
good deal less severe 
quoting testimony from several unidentified iranians the report 
refers to one witness who said five of his seven children were 
executed as suspected mujahedeen members in an alleged wave of 
executions of 20000 prisoners since the end of the iraniraq war 
two sons were still in prison one of them sick and the other 
paralyzed as the result of torture according to the witness 
but the report also notes that several people told the 
investigator that they had been wrongly listed by the mujahedeen as 
victims of executions it also included a list of various alleged 
acts of terrorism by the mujahedeen it said some witnesses said 
they had been induced to show selfinflicted marks of torture to 
enhance the false propaganda spread by the resistance 
the mujahedeen in a statement sent to news agencies denounced 
the report as the result of an ominous pact between the un 
center for human rights and the most abominable regime of our 
times galindo pohl the statement said takes the side of the 
executioner rather than the victim 
describing a visit to tehrans notorious evin prison galindo 
pohl said he was welcomed by a choir and a small band made up of 
prisoners in the presence of evin officials he talked to the 
former secretary general of the outlawed tudeh party who told of 
being tortured and showed his partially paralyzed hands and crushed 
fingers 
prisoners in the womens section told galindo pohl they had not 
been tortured or subjected to ill treatment 
in addition to the former tudeh leader the report lists six 
other witnesses as describing having undergone torture one said 
that about 90 percent of all evin prison inmates had been either 
severely tortured or submitted to treatment akin to torture 
but the report also listed four other witnesses in addition to 
the evin women prisoners who said they had never seen or heard of 
torture cases except occasional slapping 
</TEXT>
