<TEXT>
the drop that has rocked the tokyo stock 
exchange during the past few days has so far caused little more 
than a ripple on wall street 
analysts see plenty of cause for caution about the us 
financial outlook as a result of the japanese markets slide which 
intensified monday with its secondlargest point decline ever 
but the worries of many us observers have been tempered by a 
belief that the selling might prove to be primarily a 
correction of speculative enthusiasm that has been unique to 
tokyo trading for years 
with a 45 percent decline monday the nikkei average of 225 
japanese stocks extended its fall since the start of 1990 to more 
than 14 percent 
in new york by contrast the dow jones average of 30 
industrials rose 3829 points to 260248 on monday narrowing its 
loss for the year to date to 55 percent 
the comparatively better performance by american stocks during 
that period is something of a rarity 
two decades ago the leading indexes of american and japanese 
stocks stood at about the same absolute level by the end of 1989 
riding the crest of their countrys long industrial and commercial 
boom japanese prices were about 12 times higher than their us 
counterparts 
along the way shares in tokyo reached levels considered 
outlandish by traditional wall street standards such as the ratio 
of stock prices to the earnings per share of the companies involved 
recently priceearnings ratios in japan have been as high as 60 
to one compared with about 12 to one in the united states despite 
numerous arguments that the figures arent directly comparable and 
that japanese business has earned the extra recognition many us 
analysts have remained unconvinced 
american investors have thought for at least five years that 
the tokyo market was grossly overvalued said robert stovall 
president of the new york money management firm 
stovalltwentyfirst advisors 
the drop in tokyo has been accompanied by a fierce debate over 
the computerdriven strategies known as program trading with 
expectations increasing that japanese officials will soon move to 
curtail this type of activity 
thats all too familiar to participants in the american markets 
where similar trading which critics say makes stock prices more 
volatile has stirred similar controversy for several years 
i think its exactly the same thing said suresh bhirud an 
analyst at oppenheimer amp co in new york 
many american analysts acknowledge that us views of the 
japanese market are influenced by a streak of international 
competitiveness if not jealousy they also point out that as 
japanese stocks have slumped the dollar has risen in value against 
the yen in world currency markets 
its good for the dollar and its good for the american 
psyche stovall said the japanese are proving to be human 
whatever emotional satisfaction it may offer in american 
financial circles however there is also widespread concern that 
the tokyo decline may have a widening negative impact if it 
continues much longer 
for starters a pinch on japanese investors could induce them to 
pull money out of markets around the world such as the us 
treasury bond market where they have been playing an active role 
in addition analysts say the drop in the tokyo market has been 
prompted by rising interest rates in many of the worlds financial 
capitals that may be increasing the odds of a worldwide recession 
thom brown an analyst at rutherford browth amp catherwood inc 
in philadelphia says it would be reckless to ignore trouble 
warnings about the japanese market simply because they have proved 
incorrect so far 
to reiterate this warning does sound like crying wolf he 
said but remember the fable the wolf finally arrived 
