president bush on monday invited 
representatives of the worlds largest industrial nations 
including the soviet union to a midapril conference in washington 
on global warming and other environmental problems 
the conference scheduled for april 1718 will be devoted to 
science and economics issues involved in the controversy 
according to a white house statement 
bush whose stance on global warming has been derided by 
environmentalists as too proindustry had promised such a session 
after his december meeting in malta with soviet president mikhail 
s gorbachev 
about 20 nations were invited to the conference including the 
worlds major industrial powers and several nations such as 
brazil with large land masses aides said 
the administration considers the conference a vital next step 
in a joint international approach to address possible changes in 
the global environment the white house statement said 
during his 1988 presidential campaign bush cited increasing 
evidence that the earths atmosphere was heating up because of 
the socalled greenhouse effect and promised to convene a 
global conference to find ways of dealing with the problem 
more recently however bush has softened his approach saying 
that the problem needs further study 
in a speech that provoked widespread criticism from his 
audience bush told an international conference on climatic change 
earlier this month that our policies must be consistent with 
economic growth 
he suggested that in some areas of the debate politics and 
opinion have outpaced the science 
white house spokesman stephen hart said that the april 
conference was an attempt to find some common ground among 
scientific environmental and economic interests and not the 
envirnomental summit bush had called for in his campaign 
the white house statement said bush had designated as 
cochairmen of the conference william reilly administrator of the 
environmental protection agency michael boskin the chairman of 
the white house council of economic advisers and dr d allan 
bromley the presidents science adviser 
hart said that invited nations were asked to send their leaders 
own top environmental scientific and economic advisers to the 
conference 
the global conference bush had advocated during his campaign 
would have included both the soviet union and china while the 
soviet union is on the list of those invited to the april 
gathering china is not 
we would have obvious problems in terms of inviting china 
because of the current political situation said a white house 
aide who asked for anonymity this conference is not 
allinclusive its just a cross section 
officials from several european countries including norway 
denmark and sweden have argued that enough scientific knowledge 
has been accumulated about the causes of global warming to warrant 
a commitment from industrial nations to at least stabilize carbon 
dioxide pollution at current levels over the next decade 
like a greenhouse such pollution traps heat and reflects it 
back to earth causing a warming of the atmosphere while there is 
little dispute that greenhouse gases are increasing there remains 
disagreement within the scientific community as to how severe the 
warming will become and what effect it might have on the earth 
</TEXT>
