president bush hailed violeta chamorros upset 
election in nicaragua as a clear mandate for peace and 
democracy monday and his spokesman said bush wanted to lift us 
trade sanctions that have hobbled the countrys economy 
bush said the vote to oust leftist president daniel ortega 
moves us one step closer to the day when every nation in this 
hemisphere is a democracy he called for a peaceful transfer of 
power from the sandinista government that has ruled for 10 years 
in a message aimed both at the sandinistas and the 
ussupported army of contra rebels who tried to overthrow the 
government bush said given the clear mandate for peace and 
democracy there is no reason at all for further military activity 
from any quarter 
later monday the president phoned mrs chamorro to congraulate 
her on her victory the president said the election reinforces 
the nicaraguan peoples commitment to the peace process and towards 
building a free and open society said white house spokesman 
marlin fitzwater 
bush told mrs chamorro the election was a great day for the 
nicaraguan people fitzwater said 
the spokesman said bush also discussed the situation with a 
number of allied leaders 
there were immediate calls in congress for aid for mrs 
chamorros government which is to be inaugurated april 25 
we must provide her new government with aid and lets not kid 
ourselves it will take big bucks said senate minority leader 
bob dole rkan nobody said democracy was cheap said house 
foreign affairs committee chairman dante fascell dfla 
however others cautioned that with a growing line of potential 
new foreign aid recipients poland hungary czechoslovakia 
panama and others it would be difficult to promise any quick 
major grants 
mrs chamorros election was a sweet victory for the us 
government which had spent hundreds of millions of dollars in 
military and other assistance to arm the contras and keep them 
going and had also clamped economic sanctions on nicaragua 
in riverside calif vice president dan quayle praised the 
contras saying the contras were an important force throughout 
to bring democracy 
ortega was a major irritant to the white house and a frequent 
target of derision from presidents reagan and bush as recently as 
october bush ridiculed ortega at a summit of latin leaders in 
costa rica as this little man and as that unwanted animal at 
a garden party 
changing his tune bush publicly congratulated ortega monday for 
allowing a free and fair election and pledging to abide by its 
results moreover bush said there is space in a democratic 
nicaragua for all political points of view 
reagan whose administration played a major role in arming the 
contras said that the people of nicaragua and the cause of 
democracy have won an impressive and important victory and that 
now is the time for all parties to put down their weapons and 
join in a common pursuit of what is in the best interests of the 
nicaraguan people 
american supporters of the sandinista government expressed 
disappointment at the election outcome but also said that the 
election was fair 
the rev william sloane coffin said the vote was largely one 
to end the killing a vote for peace that the united states had 
shattered for years by arming the contras it was also a vote 
for food which our unilateral embargo had helped deny nicaraguan 
families 
secretary of state james a baker iii pointedly said the 
international community will insist that the decision of the 
nicaraguan people be respected and that full civil and military 
power be transferred to the newly elected government 
bush said we hope that all sides in this hotly fought contest 
will extend the hand of reconciliation and cooperate together in 
rebuilding their country for the good of all nicaraguans 
he said he had talked with venezuelan president carlos andres 
perez about appropriate trade and economic measures that we can 
take to support the new government of nicaragua 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said bush wanted the lift 
us sanctions as soon as it is feasible he said he expected 
there would be a decision fairly soon 
the sanctions will expire may 1 unless bush extends them some 
officials are recommending bush lift them much sooner if the 
sandinistas show a disposition to respect the election results 
these officials contend that early action on the sanctions would 
enable nicaragua to get a head start on economic recovery 
we certainly feel a special responsibility for the people of 
nicaragua and the courageous actions that they have taken to bring 
these elections about fitzwater said 
he also suggested the white house will seek more humanitarian 
aid for the contras many of whom are camped just outside nicaragua 
in honduras after their us funds run out this week 
the trade embargo against nicaragua was imposed on may 1 1985 
by thenpresident reagan it barred imports from nicaragua and 
banned us exports to that country except to support the contra 
rebels it also prohibited nicaraguan aircraft or boats from 
entering the united states 
mrs chamorro 60 the publisher of the opposition newspaper la 
prensa had been criticized by ortega as an instrument of us 
policy she headed the united nationalist opposition a fractious 
alliance of 14 parties ranging from far right to far left 
any friend of democracy can take heart in the fact that 
violeta chamorro won the election and the election process is 
a credit to the people of nicaragua who chose to determine their 
nations future at the ballot box bush said and that is a 
victory for democracy 
bush said for years the people of nicaragua have suffered 
and today the people of nicaragua have spoken 
the president learned of mrs chamorros victory in a 430 am 
telephone call from baker 
baker in turn had been called 15 minutes earlier by former 
president jimmy carter in managua where he was leading a team of 
election observers 
fitzwater said bush called british prime minister margaret 
thatcher french president francois mitterrand and mexican 
president carlos salinas to thank them for the support they had 
exhibited over the past months for the return to a democratic 
process in nicaragua 
and canadian prime minister brian mulroney called bush to 
discuss the election and to voice support for the transfer to 
democratic rule fitzwater said 
fitzwater said that bush in meetings through the day with top 
aides on the election outcome was very calm and concerned that 
we give full credit to the people of nicaragua 
