<TEXT>
a pregnant cancer patient who refused 
chemical and radiation therapy so the fetus wouldnt be harmed gave 
birth to a boy and mother and child appeared to be doing well 
monday 
this baby is perfect linda babcock said from her room at 
st joseph medical center in this central illinois city to think 
that i might have aborted him i think i would have died too 
the clinton woman who has three other children ages 8 to 18 and 
said she was in her 30s was diagnosed last august as having 
inoperable form of lung cancer known as oat cell carcinoma 
untreated her chances appeared slim 
textbooks say untreated oat cell cancer patients will live two 
to four months said dr james wade iii director of medical 
oncologyhematology at decatur memorial hospital 
the chances of her being able to deliver the baby without 
treatment are slim he said during the pregnancy 
on friday dr harold a nord of bloomington delivered jesse 
warren babcock weighing 5 pounds and 6 ounces 
its pretty incredible that if she has oat cell carcinoma as 
the tests have shown that she went throughout pregnancy without 
her physical condition deteriorating nord said monday in 
fact in the last few weeks she seemed to be getting better 
i was amazed this is the first time ive had a patient 
who had this condition known to be fatal and survived said 
nord who has been in obstetrics for seven years 
mrs babcock said an xray was taken after the delivery and she 
was told her condition was unchanged it hasnt changed since the 
very first diagnosis she said 
but mrs babcock said she believes she no longer has cancer and 
will continue to do without normal therapy 
i feel so much better she said i can breathe i could 
tell it was there before it felt like something cutting off my 
air taking my life 
after the diagnosis last summer mrs babcock faced hard 
choices should she undergo conventional radiation and chemical 
cancer therapy which could extend her life but harm the baby 
should she forgo treatment and hope for the best should she have 
an abortion 
after agonizing about the choices with her husband george a 
control technician at a nuclear power plant mrs babcock decided 
no chemotherapy no radiation treatment no abortion 
she adopted a program based on nutrition lots of carrot juice 
organically grown vegetables and fruits plenty of purified water 
lots of vitamin pills and faith in god 
sometimes the art of medicine is not so certain nord said 
after the successful birth 
give god the credit mrs babcock said he guided me 
through people i met books i read so many people helped me 
prayed for me ill never be able to thank them enough 
mrs babcock and her baby are to go home tuesday 
im confident of living of beating the cancer she said 
the baby saved me from death as i saved him 
