<DOCNO> AP900226-0181 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the first order of business for the united 
states in the 1990s seems to be getting rid of the detritus of the 
80s 
that theme applies in literal terms to the pollutants garbage 
and deterioration left over from a long period of exuberant 
consumption and fast track living 
no coincidence then that environmental cleanup and waste 
management rank high on just about any forecasters list of growth 
industries for the new decade 
the principle also extends in a figurative sense to clearing 
away whats left of many financial and commercial ventures of the 
past 10 years that have either gone sour or simply worn out their 
welcome 
thus we have the governments program to try to sell assets of 
hundreds of failed savings institutions and the sudden departure 
of drexel burnham lambert from the wall street scene 
such spring cleanings in the economy are usually painful 
rancorous and expensive just ask the people who lose their jobs in 
the process or the taxpayers who often wind up footing the bill 
but if all goes according to plan they are supposed to produce 
beneficial results too 
thats the way it happened 10 years ago when the economy went 
in for its last fullscale overhaul 
then the primary target for purging was rapid inflation left 
over from the stagnant 70s the measures employed were drastic a 
new economic philosophy a new tax system and even the ouster of 
an incumbent president jimmy carter 
whether by chance or by design the effort succeeded opening 
the way for a durable economic boom 
now the chief villain almost everyone agrees is debt federal 
budgetdeficit debt corporate takeover debt illadvised bank 
debt real estate debt and consumer debt 
as the bill from the savings and loan debacle mounts in 
multimilliondollar increments observes economist edward yardeni 
at prudentialbache securities the financial system is a mess 
it remains to be seen just how difficult or maybe even 
dangerous the cleanup will be but there is abundant evidence that 
it already has begun with what rao chalasani an analyst at the 
investment firm of prescott ball amp turben inc describes as 
marketinduced credit rationing 
oncebold lenders of many types ranging from large banks to 
small investors eager to buy shares of junkbond mutual funds have 
turned very stingy with their money 
that point was driven home when drexel burnham one of the prime 
promoters and beneficiaries of the debt boom expired when its own 
supply of credit was cut off neither private financial 
institutions nor government regulators showed any interest in 
coming to the firms rescue 
credit rationing is a result of the abuses of the past and a 
needed cleansing process chalasani maintains it may well hurt 
economic output shortterm he says but it increases the 
longterm stability of the economy 
as in many another freemarket shakeup what looms as a crisis 
for many has also been perceived as an opportunity for others 
the rising star at a financial firm these days displacing the 
traders and dealbrokers of yore may be a workout specialist 
who tries to salvage something of value from a bad real estate 
investment or a failed business buyout 
martin sass president of a new york moneymanagement firm that 
bears his name sees a basic investment theme for the 1990s in 
distressed bonds and real estate properties that might sooner 
or later recover at least some of their lost market value 
though a strategy of that kind naturally involves risks he 
says with storm clouds looming as we head into the 1990s we 
believe the most timely and attractive opportunities are emerging 
from what might be termed the wreckage of the 1980s 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

