<DOCNO> AP900226-0199 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when the roches sisters maggie terre and 
suzzy sing harmony their voices dont just join they overlap 
like hands clasped in support 
their records sound as spontaneous as singalongs in the 
backseat of the car as intimate as latenight talks around the 
kitchen table 
but doubts haunt these family hearttohearts on their seventh 
album speak question marks hang over declarations of love 
disappointments are grudgingly accepted as facts of life humor 
becomes a final defense against despair 
i think one of the reasons weve been able to keep a real 
intense sort of creative integrity going if i may be so bold is 
because we have the support of each other terre said of herself 
and her two sisters in a recent interview 
if i were one person dealing with business people and record 
people who are constantly giving feedback i wouldnt have been 
able to make it were constantly checking in checking the pulse 
of what were doing what we want to say 
music brings the good news on feeling is mutual the pace 
is relaxed easy the percussion gently keeping time the singing 
is assured even relieved the sound of three wise women gratified 
to still be together 
when youre listening to this record youre listening to 
people who have been basically singing together at least 20 years 
which is a very seasoned blending of voices suzzy said i 
think it would be hard to arrive at that without time 
the roches grew up in park ridge nj winning local talent 
shows and attracting enough attention for maggie and terre to tour 
folk clubs around the country younger sister suzzy at first 
staying behind 
avowed fans of paul simon upon learning that he had expressed 
interest in their singing backup on his 1973 album there goes 
rhymin simon the roches decided to accept his offer without 
bothering to tell him 
we kind of crashed the session terre recalled we had 
three days off because a gig had been canceled so we took the bus 
from pittsburgh down to muscle shoals ala and we just showed up 
at his studio and said we heard that you wanted us to sing 
there was a moment when we first arrived maggie added 
and they all had gone out to lunch the person didnt know who we 
were and we said were looking for paul simon and he sort of went 
into this get away from here mode 
only maggie and terre appeared on their debut album seductive 
reasoning in 1975 but suzzy permanently joined them for the 
acclaimed the roches released four years later 
i gotta dance to keep from crying smokey robinson once 
sang and the roches seemed to understand camping their way 
through lost love menial jobs and anxiety about health food the 
sound was all natural featuring acoustic guitars and proudly 
undubbed vocals 
a decade later the production is more polished and the only 
outandout laughs come on the antisex backlash of the 80s 
suzzys selected transcript of a conversation between her sisters 
otherwise the mood is more reflective sentimental as the roches 
sing of listening to rain falling in the darkness and proudly 
declare i love my mom 
i think people who tend to see what were doing as being 
humorous it always strikes me that theyre not looking at it 
closely enough terre said 
a lot of situations you run into the very edge of sadness or 
trouble usually sort of turns into something thats almost a 
grotesque kind of humor sometimes you see a terrible accident but 
youre inclined to laugh 
big nuthin recalls the early years when the roches seemed 
just a song or concert away from commercial success terre compared 
it to the poem in which a man sees a ball of gold in the sky and 
reaches for it when the prize is finally in his hands he 
discovers the ball of gold is merely a rock 
they learned to stop reaching in 1985 after parting ways with 
warner bros minus outside pressure the roches now signed with 
mca finally relaxed handling daytoday struggles with a 
resigned shrug of the shoulders 
in a very practical sense when we separated from warner 
bros the whole question of can we make a living without the big 
machinary was such a struggle suzzy said 
even though we have the creative freedom its a struggle 
constantly and i think we did a lot of soul searching during that 
time and really came out much better for it 
we sort of turned our back on the whole record thing terre 
recalled we said were just going to write songs and perform 
on the road and then all of a sudden a record deal came along 
like when youre not trying to fall in love with somebody you fall 
in love 
</TEXT>
