<DOCNO> AP900226-0200 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
ann beattie loves childrens drawings she finds 
them wonderful even radical and regrets that those qualities are 
usually lost in the art rooms of local schools 
her own work is a careful balance between the untutored joy of a 
nursery schoolers fingerpainting and the polished craft of a 
professional portrait its a twostep process the author says 
writing and editing the secrets and surprises of first putting the 
words on paper and the often chilly task of elimination and 
alteration that follows 
picturing will random house 1895 her first novel in 
four years is the final product of a frustrating juggling act that 
saw 15 chapters and several working titles lie crumpled in a nearby 
wastebasket the result of a creative process with several 
unexpected agonizing plot twists 
unless you intuit correctly whether as an adult or a child 
youve just got to revise it and fix it to make it a work of art 
explained beattie 43 whose work includes the novels chilly 
scenes of winter and falling in place and the shortstory 
collections the burning house and where youll find me 
i did intuit a lot of things that i gave the wrong form for 
for instance there were fairy tales in the first or second or 
third version of this book and they were totally inappropriate 
they were good writing so what there was no reason for them to be 
there 
the novel reads like an album of deepfocus photography with 
matters small and large in sharp detail a pair of red trunks seems 
as bright as the afternoon sun the breakup of a marraige is no 
clearer than the curve of a mans fingers 
time is accelerated and stretched out the narrative a montage 
of jump cuts and lengthy flashbacks years are compressed into 
paragraphs while beattie dwells on moments for several pages 
what is time beattie wonders in picturing will 
as the child experiences it it makes no sense at all 
children have little or no sense of what goes on behind the scenes 
so when things happen they seem just to happen suddenly 
considered from the childs perspective life is always 
speeding up or going too slowly the best ideas come at bedtime 
the circus ends too soon string beans take forever to eat 
like much of her fiction the plot is secondary as beattie 
probes the lives of a group of adults and the 5yearold boy 
will who brings them together 
picturing will is divided into three sections mother 
father and child with passages from a diary woven 
throughout jody is a photographer and like beattie a resident of 
charlottesville va wayne her exhusband now lives in florida 
and mel her boyfriend works in a new york art gallery 
when i caught on to what was going on it was happening on so 
many different levels that to realize the implication of all of 
them was extremely difficult the temptation was alweys to go for 
good writing not to go for something more haunting beattie said 
facts are not so much revealed as overheard like a child with 
his ear pressed against the kitchen door characters are seen up 
close and at a distance lost in their own thoughts and found in 
the thoughts of others 
one of the working titles of the book was triptych i was 
thinking about it the way a painter would think three parts all 
reflecting one another simultaneously beattie said 
a painting has an advantage you can look at it in the novel 
you have to read 230 pages to figure out whats going on it is the 
sort of book that makes you understand only in retrospect where a 
painting can make you understand instantly 
beattie who grew up in washington studied english literature 
at american university and 18th century literature in the graduate 
program of the university of connecticut 
her work appeared in the new yorker in 1974 and two years later 
chilly scenes of winter and the shortstory collection 
distortions were published simultaneously 
the first 50 pages of chilly scenes were thrown out and what 
remained seemed disjointed a muted symphony of unfinished thoughts 
and awkward silences beatties characters survivors of the 1960s 
counterculture drifted through a series of anticlimaxes 
a fathers death is confused with memories of the days 
groceries the reconciliation of the books young couple is 
followed by a crazy womans study of snowflakes 
it would seem to me to be unfortunately selfabsorbed to 
suggest in fiction something that isnt true in life which is when 
things reach a crescendo that is indeed neatly where things end 
beattie said 
i cant think of any event in my life or any event that i have 
observed where ive had the curtain drop at the moment when the 
significant line is uttered 
she rejects the term minimalist for her terse sentences and 
semiarticulate characters its an invention of the media she 
says and not reflective of her more recent work like the 1985 
novel love always beatties most humorous book 
all artists are involved in personal quests regardless of how 
well they seem to be investigating larger matters beattie 
writes picturing will is an open book the author insists and 
many of the thirdperson observations are really her own 
there are value judgments all over the place she said 
the process of selection the process of organization its not 
whats off the page between the lines and so forth its what is 
on the page with this book it would be extremely difficult not to 
know where i stand 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

