<TEXT>
source perrier sa today said it was 
planning to restock its sparkling water on supermarket shelves in 
six to eight weeks following a worldwide recall due to benzene 
contamination 
the company from its headquarters in paris said it was 
implementing a series of stringent new inspection measures 
before production resumes including new monitoring and testing 
procedures and double filtering of the carbon dioxide gas that goes 
into its sparkling water from vergeze in france 
it said a timetable for reintroduction would be established when 
all tests are completed and the new procedures are in effect but 
estimated the familiar green bottles would be back on the shelf 
within two months 
perrier recalled 160 million bottles worldwide after benzene was 
found in some bottles overseas the company first recalled 72 
million bottles in north america attributing the problem to an 
employee who inadvertently contaminated a bottling machine by 
cleaning it with benzene 
the company later expanded the recall worldwide and acknowledged 
that benzene is found naturally in the carbon dioxide gas the gas 
is extracted separately from the spring water before the two are 
combined in the perrier plant for bottling 
perrier said the contamination occurred because workers failed 
to replace filters designed to remove the benzene from the carbon 
dioxide 
in a statement from paris where source perrier is located the 
company cited experts as saying the water source was pure and no 
ones health was ever at risk because of the benzene 
it said a small amount of minor elements is found in all 
naturally occurring gases and said all companies that use carbon 
dioxide in carbonated beverages filter the gas to remove small 
levels of such compounds 
all international medical experts and regulatory officials 
consulted on the matter confirm that the health of perrier 
consumers was never in danger the company said 
however source perrier said it was instituting new measures to 
assure the purity of its product it said the gas system would be 
checked twice a day both before and after the filtering stage the 
gas will be filtered twice and the company will conduct specific 
tests for hydrocarbonate compounds it also said backup 
verification would be conducted by an outside laboratory and a team 
of international experts 
perrier said its recall is 90 percent complete the 72 million 
bottles in north america will be destroyed and recycled in 
facilities approved by the us environmental protection agency 
several suits have been filed against perrier and its us 
affiliate perrier group of america inc of greenwich conn 
charging that customers have been damaged by the benzene 
contamination the suits filed in connecticut and pennsylvania 
seek class actions against the companies 
</TEXT>
