<TEXT>
waldenbooks is launching a new program that 
combines incentives to attract customers with a hightech purchase 
tracking system for use in individualized marketing to readers 
waldenbooks chief executive said monday 
the preferred reader program being rolled out friday is the 
latest step in waldenbooks campaign to promote itself as a 
serviceoriented retailer and distinguish itself from such 
competitors as b dalton or brentanos 
harry hoffman president and chief executive officer of the 
nations largest bookstore chain said waldenbooks will be the 
first in its field to use such a technologically sophisticated 
approach to monitor what customers buy 
we think this kind of program will build a loyal customer 
base increase our share of the market and provide people who like 
books with outstanding information and keep them more aware of 
whats happening in the book business on a monthly basis he said 
in an interview 
i think the ability to reach people who we know are interested 
in what we have is going to be a tremendous opportunity to get a 
better return from advertising than we had in the past he said 
a customer can sign up for the program in a store or by calling 
a tollfree number 
for a 10 annual membership fee preferred readers receive 10 
percent off every purchase and get back 5 for every 100 spent 
the membership fee will be cut in half to 5 during the march 
kickoff checks will automatically be accepted when shoppers show 
their preferred reader cards to cashiers 
each card will carry an individualized bar code allowing 
waldenbooks to record via computer what a customer buys the 
information will be used by waldenbooks which is based in 
stamford conn and owned by k mart corp to target specific 
tastes when sending news or special discounts by mail 
hoffman said every program member will receive a monthly 
brochure containing general information about books authors and 
similar topics 
inserts occasionally will be included science fiction fans will 
get advance notice of a pending title while mystery readers will 
receive coupons for discounts off future purchases of books in that 
genre for example 
the program being implemented at all 1250 waldenbooks stores 
eventually will replace the genre specific clubs the company has 
had for years said ron jaffe senior director of marketing new 
members no longer will be enrolled in the current clubs which 
cater to people with particular reading interests 
jaffe said in an interview that the existing clubs members of 
which will be offered free oneyear memberships in the preferred 
reader program have about 3 million people as active participants 
jaffe said the program is part of a 15 million campaign in 
waldenbooks repositioning we really hope that by doing this we 
become the bookstore of choice when someone is out buying books 
he said 
besides upgrading its use of database marketing jaffe said the 
chain over the past year or so has undertaken other changes store 
displays and category presentations have been redesigned to be more 
reader friendly and individual stores have greater flexibility 
to stock books that satisfy local market preferences 
among other benefits of the new preferred reader program 
members will be able to order books by telephone selecting from 
100000 titles available at the companys nashville tenn 
distribution warehouse operators will be able to search by 
computer for hardtofind books 
nonmembers also will be allowed to call the 800number but they 
wont be eligible for the discounted prices 
hoffman said waldenbooks will redirect a significant portion of 
its 10 million to 12 million annual advertising budget to support 
the program cutting back outlays on some conventional methods 
such as catalogs in magazines 
target marketing has advantages over the shotgun approach of 
running ads in newspapers said hoffman noting i think most 
retailers in the 90s are going to have to look at this type of 
program 
