<TEXT>
the bush administration should examine why 
government officials stood by as nations savings and loans lost 
billions of dollars a group of freemarket analysts said monday 
sampl legislation passed last august requires the treasury 
department to study the deposit insurance system to determine 
whether it encouraged sampl executives to take unwise risks 
the report due a year from now is expected to form the basis 
of the next attempt by congress to reform the financial system 
but an outline of the study fails to recognize the critical role 
in the sampl collapse played by elected and appointed officials said 
the shadow financial regulatory committee a panel of 12 experts 
from universities banks and law firms 
officials allowed sampls to paper over their weaknesses with 
accounting gimmicks and postponed closing sampls when they failed 
worsening the problem and defering it to someone elses watch the 
group said in an informal position paper 
the current system confronts authorities with a painful 
tradeoff between protecting general taxpayers economic interests 
and incurring the displeasure of politically strong regulatory 
clients and their various political allies the committee said 
to counter the problem committee members recommended that 
members of congress be required to report all efforts to win favors 
for constituent firms that estimated sampl and bank losses be put 
into regulatory agencies budgets in the year they occur and that 
most most of the agencies discretion in enforcing regulations be 
removed 
on another matter they criticized the federal reserve board for 
lending more than 1 billion at below market rates to ailing 
commercial banks in new england 
such lending from the feds discount window can serve to keep 
institutions afloat that should otherwise be closed allowing 
uninsured depositors to withdraw their money the committee said 
